Soon after the return of peace the incom- petent abbot Turold died, and the monks set themselves in earnest to repair their ruins. The foundations were laid of a new ohuroh, which took more than twenty years in building. It might not have required so long, but that, on the death of the fourth successor of abbot Turold Henry de Angeli -or of Anjou, as he is termed in the present chronicle-a relation of king Henry I. obtained from that sovereign a git of the abbacy of Peterborough. The trouble which ensued is feelingly related in the Anglo·Saxon Chronicle. The traitor abbot, a lewd hireling who plundered the floch over which he was the appointed shepherd, involved the abbey in many difficulties. He even plotted to destroy its independence by aunexing it to the abbacy of Oluni. His successor completed the new church, but not without incurring many heavy debta Asubsequent abbot dealt with usurers, and greatly increased his difficulties.
